"The longer I live, the more beautiful life becomes." Frank Lloyd Wright

The Rookery building was designed by famous Chicago architectural partners Burnham and Root. The eleven story building was completed in 1888 and was the tallest building in the world. Back then, people were afraid and didn't trust the safety of tall buildings. To show there was nothing to fear, Burnham and Root worked from offices on the eleventh floor. The Burnham Library and Root’s and Burnham's offices faced south with a clear view nine miles down the lake to see the build of the World's Columbian Exposition of 1893 which the two famous architects designed.

Adding to its impressive stature, Frank Lloyd Wright redesigned the stunning two-story, sky lit lobby in 1905. Meticulously renovated and maintained, the Rookery stands as one of the most highly recognized addresses in all of Chicago.

The Rookery Oriel staircase is a Chicago gem. As gorgeous as these stairs are, can you believe they are the fire escape out of the offices? 

Scroll through the carousel of pictures to find me sitting exactly where Burnham and Root sat in the library in their famous building, the Rookery, planning the World’s Fair.

You never really know the impact you have on others around you. You don’t know how much someone needed that smile you gave them. You never how much your kindness can change a person’s bad day. You never know how much someone needed that long hug, conversation or text message saying “hi.” 

Don’t wait to be kind. Someone out there needs it! 

Last week, my daughter had an appointment with her pediatric neurologist. These appointments can be hard for special needs parents as you’re given a list of procedures the doctor wants: EKGs, MRIs and more. I was feeling pretty down after the appointment. My daughter and I went to a cafe after in Logan Square. The cafe had stairs and no ramp. I had to carry my 6 year old in and leave here wheelchair outside. I asked the barista if it was okay to leave the wheelchair outside. He could have just said “yes.” But, his response was amazing. He said “I’ll keep an eye on it and if someone bothers with it, I’ll chase them away.” Love the support & kindness this sweet barista had for me & my special needs daughter. 

I’m thinking of turning my feed pink & red for the month of love - what do you think? Yes? No?
